\begin_layout Subsection
Measures for Scarcity and Congestion
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Heffetz finds that the degree to which people notice items tend to explain
 the corresponding (permanent) income elasticities better.
 This observation has been provided basis inspection of visible consumption
 for many works.
 In an environment of inequalities, one may need to understand whether the
 rich would notice something different from what the poor notice.
 The research in developing countries points out the effect of social classes
 on visible preference.
 Moreover, the consumption in developing countries as would the state of
 being a less individualist agrarian society (where expenditure is more
 visible).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For visibility to bear significance in an environment of severe inequalities
 and scarcities, an association with higher-income beomes necessary.
 Zahra et al perform a slightly more detailed survey - by asking what would
 a person whose consumption is noticed do when her income rises (by 20%).
 This quantifies the expectations from others and assoication with higher-income
 - i.e.
 these items where consumers expect the consumption to rise are those that
 they associate with higher income.
 The criterion isn't merely the noticeability any more.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Visible consumption - which is really the detailed mechanics of status competiti
ons.
 We don't know of visible consumption without observing what people communicate.
 Scarcity merely allows status competitions - we intend to understand the
 sarcity a bit further - if we agree that i) rich people have high status
 or high-status people tend to be either rich and/or able to avail all facilitie
s otherwise.
 If this definition is agree to - then status competitions may occur because
 people perceive scarcity and they want to purchase goods.
 The visible items are merely indications to achieve what's scarce.
 The original theory that Veblen proposed was that of consipcuous items
 - items of conquest - that are scarce.
 Scarcity is more important than noticeability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Status competitions are competitions for scarce items - more so in the developin
g countries - where mechanics of noticing each others income isn't really
 a phenomenon that exists for a lot of commodities.
 In developed countries scarcities are less - and the advertising effects
 are high expenditure help people separate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method of consumption percentiles discussed above clearly offers no
 evidence of visibilty of a chosen item.
 While an item's visual appeal cannot be estimated with expenditure surveys,
 the root-cause of status signals remains is measurable the same way.
 But the reason why status signaling exists in a society - which is measured
 by visibility survey - is not an inherent need for visible appeal for certain
 item - but the item's association with status.
 Instead of limiting ourselves to the particular mechanics of status signaling
 - where consumers buy items in a common market and (presumably) overweigh
 on items that are more noticeable - we attempt to understand the reasons
 behind status-signaling by looking at the differences in patterns between
 the richer and poorer sections of society and understanding if price is
 the only barrier that limits and how commodities may reassert.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Scarcity is measured by i) availability (electricity, food, education etc.)
 and ii) by affordability.
 Affordability is the primary criterion for scarcity.
 If the item is affordable and not available, it may still be scarce.
 Severe scarcities - which would be a physical scarcities in a Hirschian
 sense - would not permit status competitions.
 When there is medium scarcity, status competition can thrive while there
 is no status competition when there is no scarcity.
\end_layout

