\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Effect of occupation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other than the sparsity of available income data, the motivation behind
 grouping occupations is the predominance of the informal sector in Tanzania.
 A few occupations in the survey are neither well defined nor are truly
 an indicator of total income.
 The presence of categories like unpaid-family-work and of individuals with
 no-primary-job getting a significant income from their secondary occupations
 makes the task of associating the primary occupation of the household head
 with her income rather difficult (i.e.
 occupation - which is available for all household heads cannot be used
 as a proxy of household income - which is not available for all households).
 Grouping the occupations into fewer categories than in the survey (by putting
 paid/unpaid family work and agriculture under the same category for example)
 may allow for the smoothening of the effect of individual occupations and
 possibly serve as a proxy of socio-economic classes in the country.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Effect of Education Level
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the claims to be evaluated on the LSMS data is whether education
 has a significant effect on visible consumption.
 If the education level of NA is considered as none (for nearly 30% of the
 recorded individuals), then highest education level of the household held
 is found quite significant for many commodities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Effect of Immigration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With a significant migration from rural areas, one of the claims to be tested
 is whether those resident in the community spend less on positional consumption.
 While this may be significant, it is of less importance than age or household
 size.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Urbanization Effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most of Tanzania appears to be sparsely popsiulated with little access to
 basic services and it is likely that the administrative classifications
 of rural-urban areas do not reflect the consumer markets so well.
 Still, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

is_rural
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 dummy is found significant for and houserent electricity (since most of
 rural Tanzania does not have electricity).
 Even if one were to use a dummy for accessible markets (created using the
 distance from the surveyed household location to the closest daily market
 ) - the effect is not so significant factor on positional consumption.
 The region dummies - on the other hand - are found to have significance
 - indicating regional disparaties in the country.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Population density
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Population density is a crude measure for crowding in the cities.
 The regions with higher population density do have a slight effect on consumpti
on of scarce commodities.
 It is hoped that a urban/rural dummy created by classifying districts based
 on their population densities may give a more detailed effect of population
 density.
 
\end_layout

