\begin_layout Part
A Behavioural Model for Status Utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Utility and Status
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The concept of status is rather non-trivial and has characteristics of feedback
 (status may yield income through social barriers and but may requires income
 for signaling as well).
 The Ireland model used in the literature treats status-signaling as purchasing
 of visible and non-visible goods
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals"

\end_inset

.
 In the Ireland model, the combined utility for every consumer is 
\begin_inset Formula $U=F(f(v,w),s)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(v,w)$
\end_inset

 is the private utility of the consumer and status 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is assumed to be an increasing function of inference of others - 
\begin_inset Formula $s=f(v,g(v)$
\end_inset

) - with 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 denoting visual consumption and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 - the consumption that is not directly observable.
 Every consumer thus optimizes the combined private and visible utility.
 A practical consideration in the model is the separation between visible
 and non-visible consumption - a boundary that requies a socio-culutral
 judgment and has been drawn using consumer surveys in the literature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What research in the developing markets further points out is that the parameter
 of combined utilty in a simplified model - (
\begin_inset Formula $U=(1-a)\cdot f(v,w)+a\cdot f(v,g(v)$
\end_inset

) - can vary for different sections of society.
 A slight adjustment of the model may be to another parameter that indicates
 once social class.
 This is more relevant in the developing world because social status is
 yielded through social barriers in many developing countries.
 Sections of society that are endowed with a higher status capital are in
 less of a need to purchase the commodities of visible consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the analysis of LSMS data on Tanzania so far, urban/rural differences
 have signficance in the consumption of scarce commodities.
 There are two ways to incoporate this into a model of signaling - one is
 to consider these household characteristics as a class of the consumers
 - and the other is to consider these characteristics as part of visible
 consumption.
 For example, English literacy seems to have correlation with the consumption
 of certain scarce products in Tanzania and 
\bar under
may indicate that people with access to English spend less on visible commoditie
s
\bar default
.
 In the model that is to be developed, English literacy (along with urban
 residence and other characterstics significant for consumption of scarce
 commodities) would be seen as status capital.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Status capital cannot be quanitified as easily and remains a binary parameter
 in the model - uses as dummies that are found to have significant association
 with consumption of scarce commodities.
 The utility function in Ireland model can be thus viewed as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(h(v,z),w)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $v,w$
\end_inset

 are the visible and non-visible consumption quantities (respectively) -
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is a function of a a discrete variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 that denotes the social characteristic and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 - the visible consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that one needs to be careful while drawing conclusions based on consumpti
on of commodities that are themselves selected based on the percentiles
 consumption levels.
 The threshold method that we use to select scarce commodities (that are
 likely to be visible) - considers items that i) are accessible by no more
 than 50% of the consumers and ii) have their expenditure rising with permanent
 income.
 These are - by definition - items that the rich are more likely to afford.
 We cannot select items that the only richer section of society indulges
 in and claim that people spending on these selected items indicate higher
 status.
 Such a claim is only a restatement of the high permanent income and says
 nothing more substantial than that the richer population sections signal
 higher status.
 It would be a fallacy to associate visible consumption with household character
istics by only associating household characteristics with permanent income.
 The threshold method that we only measures the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

scarcity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the item (e.g.
 electricity is more scarce than food) - not status per se.
 Indeed scarcity itself has an indirect effect on status competitions which
 cannot be denied - but this effect is not verified by the threshold method
 of classifying items itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
A model for scarcity and congestion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How scarcity leads to congestion is a different process in the developing
 world.
 Recent developments have made the process similar to that in the Western
 world, but the process is limited to urban settlements - areas where people
 are more huddled.
 The urban-rural differences are stark - the price differences and life
 style choices vary.
 The scarcity of services of industrial goods (which would be a necessity
 in the Western world) is evident from the data.
 The thrust towards migratioin and the desire for industrial goods needs
 to be pinned down with the survey of previous section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just the availability of electricity may open up a lifestyle that is unknown
 in the rural world.
 It may be seem drastic that a lifestyle choice transforming good such as
 electricity is the ultimate reason for migration but that is what we intend
 to test.
 That is what we mean by congestion.
 The question we seek answer for - which of the items - between a better
 house and an electricity matters more.
 Instead of visible goods, we limit our discussion to scarce goods - items
 that open up a new set of lifestyle.
 This denial of services is key to advertising mechanisms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The denial of services is a criteria that can be used to classiy all items.
 One thinks of a directed graph - which points to items that it denies (which
 themselves can be formed with items that deny other items and so and so
 forth).
 What we're now looking for are disconnected nodes in the graph - services
 and commodities that cannot be denied by the unreachable node in the graph.
 The criteria of denying is important to be defined here.
 One can think of person who is denied food in when energy (kerosene, electricit
y etc.) is unavailable but once again, this doens't apply to the larger populatio
n.
 The criteria of denying is one that needs to confirmed with statistical
 significance.
 Again, first comes the claim (e.g.
 nuts are available only to those who buy rice) - for which there may be
 limited proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
---
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that commodities appear in clusters, it is the scarcity of items
 that drives consumption.
 Congestion - a related phenomenon - is subject to demand and supply for
 a particular commodity and can be measured.
 If we were to consider food, for example, a limited supply and overpopulation
 can increase competition - .
 Similarly, for entertainment, censorship and introduction of internet can
 create congestion.
 For housing, new constructions and overpopulation can cause congestion.
 As such, congestion is commodity-specific and a focus on selected items
 may be the only way to test whether there is disproportiante consumer spending
 on the commodity.
 The data from Tanzania so far only seems to point that availability of
 services in urban and rural area could be serving as status signals.
\end_layout

